Data Loading and Augmentations

original_data <- read.csv("2022 MLB Player Stats - Pitching.csv",sep=";")

Fix Names

original_data$Name <- iconv(original_data$Name, from = "", to = "UTF-8", sub = "")
original_data$Name <- gsub("\\*", "", original_data$Name)

Track Original Dimensions

dim(original_data)
## [1] 1081   35

Add Division Attribute

require(dplyr)
## Loading required package: dplyr

##     slice

original_data$Div <- ifelse(original_data$Tm %in% c("LAD", "SDP", "SFG", "ARI", "COL", 
                                         "SEA", "LAA", "OAK", "HOU", "TEX"), "West",
          ifelse(original_data$Tm %in% c("MIN", "CLE", "CHW", "DET", "KCR", "MIL", 
                              "STL", "CHC", "CIN", "PIT"), "Central",
          ifelse(original_data$Tm %in% c("NYY", "BOS", "TBR", "TOR", "BAL", "ATL", 
                              "PHI", "NYM", "WSN", "MIA"), "East", 
                 "MULT")))
original_data <- original_data %>% relocate(Div, .after = Lg)

Rename Columns

original_data <- original_data[, -1]
colnames(original_data) <- c("Name", "Age", "Team", "League", "Div", "Wins", "Losses", "WLPercent", "ERA","G", "GS", "GF", "CG", "SHO", "SV", "IP", "H", "R", "ER", "HR", "BB", "IBB", "SO", "HBP", "BK", "WP", "BF", "ERA+", "FIP", "WHIP", "H9", "HR9", "BB9", "SO9", "SOperBB")

Remove Duplicate Player Entries

df_grouped <- original_data %>%
  group_by(Name) %>%
  filter(if (any(League == "MLB")) League == "MLB" else row_number() == 1) %>%
  ungroup()

Add “Throws”

throws_data <- read.csv("throws.csv")
df_grouped$Throws <- throws_data[[1]]
df_grouped <- df_grouped %>% relocate(Throws, .after = Div)

Set Row Identifier to Player Names

df_grouped <- as.data.frame(df_grouped) 
#player_names <- df_grouped$Name
rownames(df_grouped) <- df_grouped$Name
df_grouped$Name <- NULL

Sort By ERA+ (Eventual Target Variable)

df_grouped <- df_grouped[order(df_grouped$'ERA+', decreasing = TRUE),]

df_grouped <- df_grouped %>% relocate('ERA+', .after = Throws)

Drop ER and ERA

ERA+ Outlier Discussion

The greatest career ERA+ of all time is 205, for Mariano Rivera. Given this, assign 205 as the cutoff for outlier values on the high end. Potential reasons for a player exceeding this in a one season sample size:

  • Elite-level reliever.

  • Extremely small sample size.

  • Abnormally “lucky” season.

outlier_cutoff <- 205
sum(df$`ERA+` > outlier_cutoff)

ERA+ Histogram

ggplot(df) +
  aes(x = `ERA+`) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, fill = "blue", color = "black") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = outlier_cutoff, color = "red") +
  ggtitle("Distribution of ERA+","Outliers to the right of red line (ERA+ > 205)") + 
  labs(x = "ERA+",y = "Number of Pitchers")

ERA+ by Principal Components

set.seed(42)
prcomp_p <- data.frame(
  prcomp(x = df_scaled_numeric)$x[,1:2],
  Name = player_names,
  Rank = df$`ERA+`
)
ggplot(prcomp_p) + 
  aes(x = PC1,y = PC2,color = Rank,label = Name) + 
  geom_point() + 
  scale_color_gradient(low = "blue", high = "red",) +
  ggtitle("PCA for Pitching Data","Red = Higher ERA+, Blue = Lower ERA+") + 
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Cluster based on presumed position

set.seed(42)

zeroes <- rep(0, length.out = length(colnames(df_scaled_numeric)))
starting_pitchers <- zeroes
starting_pitchers[which(colnames(df_scaled_numeric)=="GS")] <- 3
closing_pitchers <- zeroes
closing_pitchers[which(colnames(df_scaled_numeric)=="G")] <- 3
other_pitchers <- zeroes

initial_centers <- matrix(
  data = c(starting_pitchers, closing_pitchers, other_pitchers),
  nrow = 3,
  byrow = TRUE
)
rownames(initial_centers) <- c("starters","closers/relievers","other")
kmeans_customCenters <- kmeans(x = df_scaled_numeric, centers = initial_centers)
#kmeans_customCenters$centers

prcomp_custom <- data.frame(
  prcomp(
  x = df_scaled_numeric)$x[,1:2],
  Name = rownames(df_scaled_numeric),
  Rank = df_scaled_numeric$`ERA+`,
  Cluster = as.character(kmeans_customCenters$cluster)
)
ggplot(prcomp_custom) + 
  aes(x = PC1,y = PC2,color = Cluster) + 
  geom_point() + 
  ggtitle("PCA for Pitching Data","Color determined by custom cluster participation") + 
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Red = C1 / Starters, Green = C2 / Relievers+Closers, Blue = C3 / No Distinction

set.seed(42)
# Scale everything but ERA+. Its format is scaled and the interpretation is not something I want to lose.
df_var_sel <- df %>% mutate(across(where(is.numeric)& !all_of("ERA+"), scale))

baseline_lm <- lm(`ERA+` ~ ., data = df_var_sel)
stepwise_model <- step(baseline_lm, direction = "both", 
                       k = log(nrow(df_var_sel)), trace = FALSE)

  • Wins (W)

  • Runs (R)

  • Batters Faced (BF)

  • Walks / 9 Innings Pitched (BB9) - removed

  • Strikeouts / Walk (SOperBB) - removed

Split Data

set.seed(42) 
train_indices <- sample(1:nrow(df_final), size = 0.8 * nrow(df_final))
train_data <- df_final[train_indices, ]
test_data <- df_final[-train_indices, ]

actuals <- test_data$`ERA+`

Linear Regression

set.seed(42)
lin_reg_1 <- lm(`ERA+` ~ ., data = train_data)
#summary(lin_reg_1)

preds_lm <- predict(lin_reg_1, test_data)

rmse_lm <- sqrt(mean((preds_lm - actuals)^2))
mae_lm <- mean(abs(preds_lm - actuals))
r_squared_lm <- cor(preds_lm, actuals)^2

#cat("RMSE:", rmse_lm, "\nMAE:", mae_lm, "\nR-squared:", r_squared_lm)

  Predicted_ERA_Plus = round(preds_lm,2)
)

Linear regression displays very poor metrics so far. Lets see if using cross validation could help.

XGBoost

set.seed(42)

X_train <- as.matrix(train_data %>% select(-`ERA+`))
y_train <- as.matrix(train_data$`ERA+`)
X_test <- as.matrix(test_data %>% select(-`ERA+`))
y_test <- as.matrix(test_data$`ERA+`)

xgb_model <- xgboost(data = X_train, label = y_train,
  nrounds = 100,
  eval_metric = "rmse",
  verbose = 0
)

y_pred <- predict(xgb_model, X_test)

mae_xgb <- mean(abs(y_pred - y_test))
rmse_xgb <- sqrt(mean((y_pred - y_test)^2))
r2_xgb <- 1 - sum((y_test - y_pred)^2) / sum((y_test - mean(y_test))^2)


importance <- xgb.importance(model = xgb_model)

results_xgb <- data.frame(
  Actual_ERA_Plus = actuals,
  Predicted_ERA_Plus = round(y_pred,2)
)

xgb_plot <- ggplot(results_xgb, aes(x = Actual_ERA_Plus, y = Predicted_ERA_Plus)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6, color = "blue") +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0, color = "red", linetype = "dashed") +
  ggtitle("ERA+ Prediction vs Actual Values", "XGBoost") + 
  labs(x = "Actual ERA+",y = "Predicted ERA+")

Success with outliers vs normal data

outlier_predictions <- subset(results_xgb, Actual_ERA_Plus > 205)
normal_predictions <- subset(results_xgb, Actual_ERA_Plus <= 205)

mean(abs(outlier_predictions$Actual_ERA_Plus - outlier_predictions$Predicted_ERA_Plus))
## [1] 131.7567
mean(abs(normal_predictions$Actual_ERA_Plus - normal_predictions$Predicted_ERA_Plus))
## [1] 14.10955

xgb.plot.importance(importance)

Conclusion

Key insights from entire project

  • Pitchers with better (higher) ERA+ values profile more as relievers or closers, and teams may consider moving starters with such stats to higher leverage positions.

  • A league average pitching staff or better should be a priority for teams attempting to compete.

  • Handedness (L vs R) may matter in certain match ups, but is not a significant factor in ERA+ at a season-wide scale.

  • Age is not a major factor in ERA+, until a player reaches an older stage of their careers, experiencing physical decline.

  • The XGBoost model outperformed others, slightly edging out SVR, making it the most effective model for ERA+ prediction given the current dataset. Performs very well on normal data, struggles with outliers.

  • Among all predictors, WHIP emerged as the strongest predictor of ERA+, and is a core metric team executives and coaches should refer to when evaluating pitcher performance.
